Git-commit: 07853adc29a058c5fd143c14e5ac528448a72ed9
References: CVE-2022-49610 bsc#1238952
From: Juergen Gross <jgross@suse.com>
Date: Tue, 14 Jun 2022 23:16:16 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] KVM: VMX: Prevent RSB underflow before vmenter

On VMX, there might be a return between the time the guest's
SPEC_CTRL value is written, and the vmenter. This can happen in case
x86_virt_spec_ctrl() isn't inlined for some reason.

In order to avoid that, tag x86_virt_spec_ctrl() with "always_inline".

[Completely different solution than upstream, but without any call
 between x86_virt_spec_ctrl() and vmenter in vmx_vcpu_run(), the
 solution of the problem is much easier.]

Signed-off-by: Juergen Gross <jgross@suse.com>
---

diff --git a/arch/x86/include/asm/spec-ctrl.h b/arch/x86/include/asm/spec-ctrl.h
index 437308004ef2..cb50589a7102 100644
--- a/arch/x86/include/asm/spec-ctrl.h
+++ b/arch/x86/include/asm/spec-ctrl.h
@@ -23,7 +23,7 @@
  *
  * Avoids writing to the MSR if the content/bits are the same
  */
-static inline
+static __always_inline
 void x86_spec_ctrl_set_guest(u64 guest_spec_ctrl, u64 guest_virt_spec_ctrl)
 {
 	x86_virt_spec_ctrl(guest_spec_ctrl, guest_virt_spec_ctrl, true);
